In .NET MAUI, the equivalent is to use **Window lifecycle events** instead of the legacy `Application` overrides:

| Xamarin.Forms | .NET MAUI Window Event |
|---|---|
| `OnStart` | `Activated` (or `Created` for one-time init) |
| `OnSleep` | `Stopped` |
| `OnResume` | `Resumed` |

Override `CreateWindow` in your `App` class:

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
    {
        var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);

        window.Created   += (s, e) => { /* one-time init (was OnStart) */ };
        window.Stopped   += (s, e) => { /* app backgrounded (was OnSleep) */ };
        window.Resumed   += (s, e) => { /* app foregrounded (was OnResume) */ };

        return window;
    }
}
```

Or subclass `Window` and override the virtual methods directly:

```csharp
public class AppWindow : Window
{
    public AppWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }

    protected override void OnActivated() { /* refresh UI */ }
    protected override void OnStopped()   { /* save state */ }
    protected override void OnResumed()   { /* restore state */ }
}
```

**Key differences to know:**

1. **`Resumed` doesn't fire on first launch** — the initial sequence is `Created` → `Activated`. Use `Activated` if logic must run on every foreground entry.
2. **Android back button can skip `Stopped`** — also save state in `OnDestroying`.
3. The old `OnStart`/`OnSleep`/`OnResume` still compile but bypass Window-level events and don't support multi-window scenarios. Prefer the Window events.
